!About Time\n\nMeanwhile, in a small trouser dimension located slightly north of Earth, a man we presumed to be dead sat at a gleaming Steelium^^TM^^ desk. The surface reflected an image he hadn’t seen in a long time: a face topped by a mop of unkempt gray-brown hair and outlined by a scraggly beard of similar color, a face from which eyes of two distinct colors seemed to pierce his soul. He saw his black and red Hawaiian shirt, and through its many tears, his bruise-colored undershirt. And he saw a few of the many watches he wore peeking out from underneath it. He had always liked this look, it—\n\n“Are we making a habit of this, Mr. Rowe?” asked a stern voice that had no clear origin. Mr. Rowe was the name the man manufactured for himself the last time he died.\n\n“Mr. Rowe” remained silent, like a small child resigning himself to a timeout.\n\n“I asked, ‘Are we making a habit of this, Mr. Rowe?’”\n\nThe man looked up and saw an Angel. Angels were . . . less than popular among the denizens of every universe. As individuals, they had no defining characteristics. Each one wore the same silky black robes and covered their faces with the same white hood, and from each of their backs protruded a pair of albino bat wings, which were rather less <abbr title="Angels are approximately the size of a human, but their wings are still on the scale of a fruit bat. Even evolution needs a good laugh sometimes.">functional</abbr> than any of them would like to admit.\n\n“You know very well that I can’t help it when I die.”\n\n“Perhaps, but every time you arrive in the afterlife, you try to escape. We’ve been compassionate thus far; you’ve had eight additional chances at life. The only creature we allow this many chances is the domesticated Earthian house cat. I believe it would be redundant to tell you that you are not, in fact, an Earthian house cat.”\n\n“You’re right, I’m not a house cat. But it doesn’t matter. After all, I’m just going to escape again.”\n\n“We have taken certain precautions this time.” \n\nThis statement through the man for a loop. Angels were perhaps the most prideful intelligent life forms in the galaxy. They never learned, they never changed. They just couldn’t bear to admit it when they were wrong. If they were this desperate, then he needed get out of hell—preferably twenty minutes ago.\n\n“What’s your name, Angel?”\n\n“Fred.”\n\n“Nice to meet you, Fred. I assume you’re the Angel I’ve dealt with in the past?”\n\n“I cannot say, Mr. Rowe.” \n\nHearing this, the man reached for his magnum. \n\n“We have confiscated your Improbability Trigger, Mr. Rowe. We are well aware of its potential to aid in your escape.”\n\n“Ah, you must be new, then,” said the man as he quickly removed one of his watches and threw it into the Angel’s hood.\n\n“I don’t know what you think you’re doing, Mr. Rowe.”\n\n“Fred, I’m so sorry about this. But you need to understand, a mystery is afoot, and I have to solve it. The watch now falling through the abyss behind you hood happens to be a trans-dimensional key. It unlocks universe [=^.^=], the universe I created to store my gun. The Improbability Trigger and [=^.^=] are intimately connected. Like I said, I’m so, so sorry.”\n\nAt that moment, Fred coughed up a cat. And another cat. And another cat. Suffice to say, more than a few cats appeared from the depths of Fred’s hood. Eventually, the torrent stopped, producing just one more of the anaerobic felines found within [=^.^=]. Sporting an adorable little fishbowl around its adorable little head and a weathered watch around its neck—the key to the universe—it clutched the not-so-adorable Improbability Trigger within its adorable little paws. Mr. Rowe scooped the cat from the floor, <abbr class="aside" title="Writer's Note: For those of you with a keen eye for detail, this is not, in fact, a typo.">scratched its head</abbr>, and took from it his gun.\n\n“That feels much better,” he said. With a snap of his fingers, the rest of the cats jumped back to [=^.^=]. Looking at the fallen Angel with something close to sympathy, then back to his new companion, Mr. Rowe said, “I’m going to call you Freddie.” Then he walked out the door.

!Down Under in Space\n\nAs he approached Earth, the man froze. His mind raced. Why was he going to Earth? Why was he going home? He didn’t remember home. He’d lost his memories. \n\nHe smiled. There was a conspiracy afoot. The world was sane again.\n\nThen the Earth blew up and rather ruined the moment.\n\n“Damn it, universe! I was having a moment here!” A kangaroo flew past. The man didn’t know a kangaroo flew past. His ship didn’t have windows, remember? Of course, as with everything in the universe, the kangaroo had an origin. That origin was a particular chunk of Australia. That particular chunk of Australia was now in a particular chunk of spacetime. And moving toward another particular chunk of spacetime. Naturally, the universe being the sadistic, insensitive, not-so-sentient vastness that it is, the particular chunk of Australia hit the particular chunk of spacetime in which the man’s ship was located.\n\nThe escape pod was destroyed and the man killed. Oh well.\n\n[[Next chapter . . .|Chapter 3]]
!Metallin Customer Service Is Horrible\n\n“Oh well? OH WELL? You are trying my patience, Mr. Sebastian!”\n\n“I . . . I know ma’am. It was an unfortunate setback. The culprit is being punished as we speak, ma’am.”\n\n“I hope you mean executed. You know very well that I do not tolerate failure.”\n\n“Um, no, ma’am. I’ll relay the order to the Torturer immediately, ma’am,” squeaked Mr. Sebastian. Cormac Sebastian was a small, portly little man with <abbr title="That is to say, as much hair as no hair at all. That is to say, he was bald.">as much hair as he had spine</abbr>. He was hired by the woman currently scolding him for his incredible organizational skills, unswerving loyalty, and his access to a not unimpressive collection of chainsaws. (He didn’t know she knew about the chainsaws, of course; it didn’t do to let people know about the chainsaws.)\n\n“Good. Now that I’ve been informed what has happened, would you care to explain why the help decided to kill the target rather than restrain him?”\n\n“No, ma’am. Sorry, ma’am. I can have the Torturer find out, ma’am, if you’d like. Ma’am.”\n\n“You shouldn’t need to. You hired him. Why would he blow up the planet?”\n\n“I’m sorry, ma’am, but I really don’t know.”\n\n“Oh, Cormac, what am I going to with you?”\n\nMr. Sebastian tensed. His boss had never used his first name before, and he hadn’t expected her to start. Ever. He knew what was coming a moment before it happened. It was a long moment. His boss pulled a vintage magnum out of <abbr title="Actually she pulled it out of a parallel universe so full of anaerobic spacecats that there wasn’t any air. Semantics.">the air in front of her</abbr> and pointed it at his head. If he looked inside the gun, he would have found no ammunition. He closed his eyes. She pulled the trigger. And she kept pulling the trigger. Eventually a bullet came out and Cormac Sebastian fell over, dead. Walking calmly to her desk, she ordered a new Cormac Sebastian from the catalog.\n\nIt is, perhaps, important to understand the time frame in which these events occurred in order to better understand the circumstances and the characters involved in them. At 11:34 AM, Mr. Sebastian began to relay his dismal news to his mysterious employer. Six minutes and thirty-four seconds later, his employer began to yell. Three minutes later exactly, his employer pulled out her gun. For the next four minutes and eight seconds, Mr. Sebastian whimpered, his life flashing before closed eyes. Such an experience is typically calming; unfortunately for Cormac, his closed eyes prevented him from seeing any of it. Then he died. It took the woman twenty-two minutes and fifty-one seconds to order a new assistant. Metallin customer service is horrible.\n\n[[Next chapter . . .|Chapter 4]]
!Chapter 1: Down Under\n\nIt might have been sunny outside. It was probably sunny. It didn’t matter if it was sunny. His spaceship didn’t have windows. It was also a few miles beneath the planet’s surface. He hadn’t meant for it to get stuck there, of course, but he didn’t have much control over it. The spaceship was a battered old escape pod he “borrowed” from a Metallin gunship and jury-rigged with a <abbr title="A propulsion device capable of traversing time, space, and that stuff that exists in between parallel universes.">multiverse</abbr> engine. It was a rush job; the Metallin soldiers wouldn’t stop shooting, and he never worked up the motivation to fix it. As a result, he occasionally found himself materializing inside planets.\n\nStarting up the multiverse engine, he set his destination to a universe in which the planet was destroyed. He didn’t bother checking the planet’s name; it didn’t exist anymore. Waiting for the ship to reach it’s destination, he set about remembering his name—another unfortunate side effect of the faulty ship. Some indeterminable time ago, following what he thought was a good night’s rest, he woke up millions of years later. Suffice to say, the brain had trouble retaining memories for that long.\n\nBut it was far too late now, he knew. Those memories weren’t coming back no matter how hard he tried. As the ship neared its destination, he considered his next exploit. The entire universe was his sandbox. He turned his thoughts toward home: Earth. He hadn’t been back on Earth for eternity. Nostalgia got the better of him. He checked the console—a gray and brown screen in true Metallin fashion—to see if Earth existed in this universe. It did. He was going home.\n\n[[Next chapter . . .|Chapter 2]]
